    "/hooks/outgoing": {
      "post": {
        "summary": "Create an outgoing hook to a specific resource",
        "operationId": "addOutgoinHook",
        "tags": [
          "Hooks - Outgoing"
        ],
        "description": "The fields `target_url`, `settings.request_body` and `settings.request_headers` accept\nvariables that will be expanded when the hook is triggered. The syntax to use variables\nare using dot-notation inside `{{` and `}}` tags, for example:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"settings\": {\n    \"request_headers\": [\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Authorization\",\n        \"value\": \"Bearer {{ application.source_provider.access_token }}\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nWhere `{{ application.source_provider.access_token }}` will be expanded to access token of\nthe application related to outgoing hook by `resource_type` and `resource_id` fields.\n\nThe valid resources that can be accesed by variables are:\n* `action` - The action that have triggered the hook. The fields are the same returned\n  by the [GET /actions/{id}](#operation/getAction) endpoint,\n  e.g.: `{{ action.status }}`\n* `hook`   - The outgoing hook itself. The fields are the same returned by the\n  [GET /hooks/outgoing/{id}](#operation/getOutgoingHook) endpoint,\n  e.g.: `{{ hook.secret }}`\n* `user`   - The user that triggered the hook. The fields are the same returned by\n  the [GET /users/{id}](#operation/getUser) endpoint, e.g.: `{{ user.name }}`\n\nAnd the resource related to outgoing hook is also accessible by variables using it's\nresource name. For instance an outgoing hook related to a daemon can get the\ndaemon's command using: `{{ daemon.command }}`\n\nIf the resource is an application, the deployment resource is also accessible by\nvariables. For instance `{{ deployment.source.pull_request_id }}` to get the\npull request source information of the deployment.\n\n**Note**: usually sub-resources relations of a resource are not accessible on outgoing hooks variables. For instance\nthe `{{ daemon.project.name }}` is **not** a valid variable.\nAn exception to this rule is the `application` resource that has the `source_provider` sub-resource that exposes the additional `access_token` field, which is not public by default.\n",
        "parameters": [
          {
            "$ref": "#/components/parameters/acceptHeader"
          },
          {
            "$ref": "#/components/parameters/authHeader"
          },
          {
            "$ref": "#/components/parameters/contentTypeHeader"
          }
        ],
        "requestBody": {
          "description": "A JSON object containing outgoing hook data",
          "required": true,
          "content": {
            "application/json": {
              "schema": {
                "$ref": "#/components/schemas/HookOutgoingCreate"
              }
            }
          }
        },
        "responses": {
          "201": {
            "description": "Created",
            "content": {
              "application/json": {
                "schema": {
                  "$ref": "#/components/schemas/HookOutgoing"
                }
              }
            }
          },
          "403": {
            "$ref": "#/components/responses/Forbidden"
          },
          "404": {
            "$ref": "#/components/responses/NotFound"
          }
        }
      }
    },
